      "side": 1,
      "message": "Boy what a can of worms this turned out to be...\n\nAt a high level, I think we actually don\u0027t want to flush here.  We\u0027d rather fail with no PNG than with a half-written PNG file, right?\n\nAnyway, reading the docs would make you think you need to set this to at least a non-null noop function or the default implementation will call fflush() on our SkWStream*:\n\n    Supplying NULL for the read, write, or flush functions sets them back\n    to using the default C stream functions, which expect the io_ptr to\n    point to a standard *FILE structure.  It is probably a mistake\n    to use NULL for one of write_data_fn and output_flush_fn but not both\n    of them, unless you have built libpng with PNG_NO_WRITE_FLUSH defined.\n\nThat turns out to be incorrect for the flush function.  If you read the code, you\u0027ll see a null flush function is ignored:\n\n    void png_flush(png_structrp png_ptr)\n    {\n       if (png_ptr-\u003eoutput_flush_fn !\u003d NULL)\n          (*(png_ptr-\u003eoutput_flush_fn))(png_ptr);\n    }\n\nThis is why we can use nullptr here safely, and why SkPngEncoder, which also passes nullptr, isn\u0027t exploding catastrophically.\n\nWe could pass +[](png_structp){} as that noop if we feel like it?",
